  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_74277892" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/74277892" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/104823-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527527813p2/104823.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/74277892?book_show_action=true">Oct 12, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/104823-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=2009">2009</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=age-adult">age-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/104823-kate?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer74277892" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12302486497754155377">It&apos;s hard to believe that I went so long without having read H.P. Lovecraft, considering that I love horror and most of my favorite horror authors are influenced by his work. For some reason I thought his stories would be hard to connect with - probably because of the whole &quot;Cthulhu&quot; / made up word thing. I found three of his short story collections at the library and chose to begin with this one largely because it contained the story &quot;The Call of Cthulhu.&quot;<br/><br/>The first few short stories reminded me</span>
  <span id="freeText12302486497754155377" style="display:none">It's hard to believe that I went so long without having read H.P. Lovecraft, considering that I love horror and most of my favorite horror authors are influenced by his work. For some reason I thought his stories would be hard to connect with - probably because of the whole "Cthulhu" / made up word thing. I found three of his short story collections at the library and chose to begin with this one largely because it contained the story "The Call of Cthulhu."<br /><br />The first few short stories reminded me a lot of Edgar Allan Poe, in particular "The Picture in the House," "The Outsider," and "In the Vault" : they were short, had a lot of gothic atmosphere, and usually involved some ironic twist at the end. The other early short stories were strange and only later did I connect them to the "Cthulhu Mythos" that dominates the other half the short stories in this collection. Apparently one of the earlier stories, "The Silver Key," is the start of Lovecraft's "Dream Cycle," and I immediately thought of Joe Hill's <br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3217221.Locke___Key__Vol__1_Welcome_to_Lovecraft__Hardcover_" title="Locke &amp; Key, Vol. 1 Welcome to Lovecraft (Hardcover) by Joe Hill" rel="nofollow noopener">Locke &amp; Key, Vol. 1 Welcome to Lovecraft</a>.<br /><br />The Cthulhu stories are more science fiction or speculative fiction, and though not all of them feature that monster Cthulhu, they all involve races of alien creatures that lie somewhat dormant deep inside the earth or in the ocean or in the hills of Vermont, creatures which often inspire small cults of worship in strange places. Often there are stones with "weird geometry" covered in unknown heiroglyphs, and mysterious texts like the Necromicon and others that have instructions as to how to release the aliens from their slumber. The aliens are usually described as being of some amphibian or squid-like nature, with tentacles and green skin, which sounds completely ridiculous, but the way they are discovered in the story somehow makes it seem almost possible. Usually the main character is driven mad by the discovery of these secrets.<br /><br />This was definitely a good book to read around Halloween. I was also a bit disturbed by the geographical proximity of these stories to where I live: Lovecraft grew up in Providence, RI, but he indicates in one story a place past Fitchburg, Ayer, and Gardner, all places I've been and which are about a 20 minutes' drive from my house. I thought the "ironic twist" of some of the stories was a bit weak and obvious, but overall the bizarreness of these alien races lurking in the corners of our own society was what makes these stories memorable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12302486497754155377" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


