  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1013043772" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1013043772" />
    <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour"><img alt="J.M. Hushour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442964894p2/17463213.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1013043772?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.M. Hushour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.M. Hushour" href="/user/show/17463213-j-m-hushour">J.M. Hushour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1013043772" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15326628947712096497">My sole previous experience with Lovecraft is his fine short novel &quot;At the Mountains of Madness&quot;. Well-crafted and well-plotted, the freakish and disturbing nature of his meticulously thought-out lore comes to the fore in that and numerous other stories from his work.<br/>Herein lies the problem: Lovecraft is a fine writer, a composer that can&apos;t help but remind one of a latter-day, emotionally disturbed Dickens. His turn-of-the-word is outstanding, but highly derivative in and of itself. What I mean </span>
  <span id="freeText15326628947712096497" style="display:none">My sole previous experience with Lovecraft is his fine short novel "At the Mountains of Madness". Well-crafted and well-plotted, the freakish and disturbing nature of his meticulously thought-out lore comes to the fore in that and numerous other stories from his work.<br />Herein lies the problem: Lovecraft is a fine writer, a composer that can't help but remind one of a latter-day, emotionally disturbed Dickens. His turn-of-the-word is outstanding, but highly derivative in and of itself. What I mean here is, and this can be applied to his plotting as well, that after two or three stories, the remainder kind of fall into a predictable rut, right down to the adjectives. Will tormented narrator A, B, or C encounter cyclopean structures made out of basalt, regulated by insane, non-Euclidean geometries? You betcha! Will said narrator's torments be one of a few variants of twisted, ancient space evils that barely appear and are as easily disposed of as Ewoks? (The rebirth of Cthulhu himself is prevented by a sailor driving his boat into his groin, rather anticlimactic considering the suggested span of his dark, eldritch powers)<br />As predictable and self-reflecting as most of these stories are, there are a number that stand out. "Pickman's Model" and "The Music of Erich Zann" are great, and fall outside of the Mythos rubric for the most part. "The Shadow Out of Time" is mildly interesting, as another weird race, exuberantly and exhaustively described with their conic shapes and flailing tentacles fears the rise of the baddies populating the other stories. And there is something to enjoy in most of the ones in this collection, don't get me wrong.<br />It's just that one can get over-Lovecrafted quickly, and this is only the fault of the author. Had he expanded his repertoire of imagery and not confined himself to basically telling the same story over and over again, one can see the genius lurking beneath.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15326628947712096497" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


